# Iron Road Project Standards

## Product And Architecture
- Build a browser-first Vite/React/TypeScript game; deployed output is static files from `dist/`.
- Keep the current boundaries clear: pure game rules in `src/engine/`, authored data in `src/content/`, persistence in `src/store/`, UI in `src/ui/`.
- Prefer simple, explicit code over clever abstractions. Add helpers only when they remove real duplication or clarify a domain rule.
- Treat `IRON_ROAD_SPEC.md` as the source of product intent and `README.md` as the source for developer/deployment workflow.

## TypeScript And Code Style
- Preserve `strict` TypeScript quality: no `any`, no unused code, no silent fallthrough, no ignored errors.
- Model game behavior with typed unions, discriminated actions/effects, and exhaustive `switch` handling where practical.
- Keep functions small and named for domain intent: `resolve...`, `apply...`, `generate...`, `format...`.
- Avoid hidden mutation in engine code; return new state objects and keep reducers deterministic.
- Use comments sparingly for non-obvious rules, migrations, or domain mechanics. Do not comment what a line already says.

## React And State
- Keep React components focused on rendering, input handling, and local UI state.
- Do not put campaign rules, dice math, content generation, or save migration logic in components.
- Use Zustand stores as thin adapters around `reduceGame`; keep persistence keys and migrations deliberate.
- Prefer derived helper functions over duplicating display logic across JSX.

## Content Authoring
- Event content must validate through `RuntimeEventSchema`; update schemas and types together when the content model changes.
- Preserve event choice quality: 3-4 meaningful choices unless a flavor/social beat intentionally needs fewer.
- Give choices role coverage, recognizable risk/reward tradeoffs, and soldier-like labels instead of generic menu text.
- Keep narrative tone aligned with the spec: gritty, human, historically grounded, occasionally darkly funny.
- Use existing template placeholders and pools before inventing parallel content mechanisms.

## Testing And Verification
- Add or update Vitest coverage for reducer flows, deterministic generation, dice/rng behavior, schema/content changes, and save migration.
- Prefer focused tests that prove the changed behavior and catch regressions over broad snapshot churn.
- Run `npm test` for behavior/content changes and `npm run build` for TypeScript or bundling-sensitive changes.
- Keep tests deterministic by controlling seeds and avoiding time, randomness, or browser globals unless explicitly under test.

## Documentation And Maintenance
- Update `README.md` for workflow/deployment changes and `IRON_ROAD_SPEC.md` or `KANBAN.md` for product-scope changes.
- Document save format changes, migrations, new event/effect shapes, and player-visible mechanics.
- Do not commit generated `dist/`, local repair scripts, or one-off debugging artifacts unless the project explicitly needs them.
- Leave unrelated code alone; make the smallest coherent change that improves the game and keeps future work easier.
